{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620317"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:40:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:40:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16615"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16615"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.14,0.18,0.05,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9306"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76215"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9306"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16615"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61719"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5237"},{"type":"tags","id":"7614"},{"type":"tags","id":"7670"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22064"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76215"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAlkylating agents are a class of chemotherapy medications commonly used to treat various cancers. They work by modifying DNA structure to prevent cell division.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of alkylating agents?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Forms covalent cross-links between DNA strands","Inhibits topoisomerase enzyme function","Competes with nucleotides during DNA synthesis","Blocks DNA methyltransferase activity","Disrupts microtubule assembly"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of alkylating agents involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eforming covalent cross-links between DNA strands\u003C/strong\u003E. These agents add alkyl groups to DNA bases, creating bonds between the strands that prevent DNA separation during replication. This leads to cell death, particularly in rapidly dividing cells like cancer cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits topoisomerase enzyme function\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of topoisomerase inhibitors like etoposide and doxorubicin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetes with nucleotides during DNA synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes antimetabolites like methotrexate and 5-fluorouracil\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks DNA methyltransferase activity\u003C/strong\u003E - This is how demethylating agents like azacitidine work\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts microtubule assembly\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of antimicrotubule agents like vinca alkaloids and taxanes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon examples of alkylating agents include cyclophosphamide, busulfan, and melphalan. Their DNA cross-linking ability makes them effective chemotherapy agents but also contributes to their side effects and risk of secondary cancers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Alkylating agents cause cell death by adding alkyl groups to DNA bases, preventing DNA replication and transcription.","Cyclophosphamide, busulfan, and melphalan are common examples of alkylating agents used in cancer treatment.","Cross-linking of DNA strands is the primary mechanism by which alkylating agents prevent cell division."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61719"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16615"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61719"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T14:08:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T14:09:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9306"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76215"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"